CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is a stylesheet 
language used to describe the presentation of HTML or XML 
documents. CSS allows developers to style and format web
 pages by controlling layout, colors, fonts, spacing, and more,
  separate from the HTML content structure. In web development, 
  CSS plays a critical role in making websites visually appealing, 
  accessible, and responsive to different screen sizes and devices.

Hereâ€™s a simple example of an HTML document that includes a basic CSS
 stylesheet to style the page's background color, text color, and font size.

 HTML Document

 <!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Styled Page</title>
    <!-- Link to CSS stylesheet -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to My Styled Page</h1>
    <p>This page demonstrates basic CSS styling.</p>
</body>
</html>

CSS Stylesheet (styles.css)

/* Apply styles to the entire page */
body {
    background-color: #f0f8ff;  /* Light blue background color */
    color: #333333;             /* Dark gray text color */
    font-size: 18px;            /* Set default font size */
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;  /* Set default font */
}

/* Style for the heading */
h1 {
    color: #0056b3;  /* Dark blue text color for headings */
    font-size: 2.5em;  /* Larger font size for emphasis */
    text-align: center; /* Center-align the heading */
}


